chain_of_thought: [Article Type: Case Report] In this article, I found the following liver injury-related lab values and clinical outcomes: The patient is a 42-year-old male who used complementary and alternative medicine (CAM) for fatty liver treatment. The suspected drugs are the herbal supplements containing Carica papaya, Alstonia boonei, and Tetrapleura tetraptera. From the case presentation and Table 2, I extracted peak lab values: ALT >7000 IU/L, AST >7000 IU/L, ALP 198 IU/L (peak from table), GGT 310 IU/L (mentioned in text), Bilirubin total 6.1 mg/dL and direct 4.9 mg/dL (peak from table), INR 2.78, Albumin normal (mentioned as normal protein and albumin levels). The clinical outcome is improved/discharged as the patient showed symptomatic and biochemical improvement after discontinuation of supplements and supportive care including N-acetyl cysteine.
